SIMPLE: stoke
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stoke
<hw>Stoke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stoken</ets>, fr. D. <ets>stoken</ets>, fr. <ets>stok</ets> a stick
(cf. OF. <ets>estoquier</ets> to thrust, stab; of Teutonic origin, and
akin to D. <ets>stok</ets>). See <er>Stock</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To stick; to thrust; to stab.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor short sword for to <qex>stoke</qex>, with point biting.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To poke or stir up, as a fire; hence, to tend, as
the fire of a furnace, boiler, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stoke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stoke
<hw>Stoke</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To poke or stir up a fire; hence,
to tend the fires of furnaces, steamers, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stokehold</ent>⟦br⟧
